---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import NavBar from "../components/NavBar.astro";

const installCommand =
  "codex plugin marketplace add dianedef/ShipGlowz --ref main --sparse .agents/plugins --sparse plugins/shipflow";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Install ShipGlowz for Codex"
  description="Add ShipGlowz to Codex in a few minutes: marketplace command, plugin install path, and the first useful workflow command."
>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <NavBar />

    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Install ShipGlowz</p>
        <h1 class="page-title">Install ShipGlowz once. Stop losing time on the first move.</h1>
        <p>
          ShipGlowz is the shortest serious path from “I have work to do” to
          “the right workflow is actually running.” You install one Codex
          plugin named <code>shipflow</code>, add the marketplace source once,
          and start with one plain instruction instead of memorizing a long
          command catalog.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="#install-steps">Install ShipGlowz now</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/skills/shipflow">See what the router does</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="doc-grid">
        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>Who this is for</h3>
          <p>
            Founders, operators, and builders who want Codex to route real work
            more cleanly without starting every thread from scratch.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>What changes after install</h3>
          <p>
            You get one public entrypoint that can answer directly, choose the
            right ShipGlowz workflow, or ask one bounded clarification when the
            route is genuinely ambiguous.
          </p>
          <p>
            You can also steer the AI with simple fast tags like
            <code>#offer</code>, <code>#clarity</code>, or
            <code>#shipflow</code> instead of rewriting the whole instruction.
          </p>
          <a class="doc-action" href="/docs#recommended-combos">Open the focus-tags cheatsheet</a>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>What this is not</h3>
          <p>
            Not a pile of disconnected prompts, and not a claim that the plugin
            already contains every private reference. It is the clean public
            starting layer.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section" id="install-steps">
      <div class="doc-grid">
        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>1. Add the marketplace source</h3>
          <p>
            This tells Codex where the ShipGlowz plugin marketplace lives in the
            public repository.
          </p>
          <pre><code>{installCommand}</code></pre>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>2. Restart Codex</h3>
          <p>
            Restart Codex so the new marketplace source is loaded into the
            plugin directory.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>3. Install the plugin</h3>
          <p>
            Open the plugin directory, choose the <code>ShipGlowz</code>
            marketplace, then install the <code>shipflow</code> plugin.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>4. Start with one plain instruction</h3>
          <p>
            The fastest first-success command is:
          </p>
          <pre><code>$shipglowz help me choose the right workflow</code></pre>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="cta-panel">
        <p class="eyebrow">First-run outcome</p>
        <h2>You do not need to decide between build, bug, deploy, content, or docs first.</h2>
        <p>
          The public plugin is intentionally lightweight, but it already gives
          you the part that matters first: a visible routing layer. ShipGlowz
          can answer a simple question, choose the right workflow move, and
          keep the handoff visible in the main thread. When a workflow needs
          the fuller corpus, ShipGlowz can route you there explicitly instead of
          pretending the plugin is something it is not.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/skills/shipflow">Open the shipflow skill page</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/skill-modes">Read the workflow cheatsheet</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="doc-grid">
        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>What happens in the first five minutes</h3>
          <p>
            Install the plugin, run one plain request, and let ShipGlowz decide
            whether the next move is a build flow, bug loop, maintenance pass,
            release path, content workflow, design route, or a direct answer.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>If you need the full corpus</h3>
          <p>
            Some workflows still need the optional complete ShipGlowz source tree.
            The plugin can route you there explicitly when that happens.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>If you want the pack roadmap</h3>
          <p>
            ShipGlowz keeps one public plugin first. Internal packs remain
            packaging infrastructure until they are genuinely portable and ready
            for public installation.
          </p>
          <a class="doc-action" href="/docs">Open the docs overview</a>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>If you are still evaluating</h3>
          <p>
            Read the public skill page first. It explains what the `shipflow`
            entrypoint actually does before you commit to the wider framework.
          </p>
          <a class="doc-action" href="/skills/shipflow">Open the shipflow page</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
